Grumble!!!

How many times does it have to be spelled out in the RFC's and in
the mailing lists before the word gets out?  Does there have to be
an explicit RFC on this topic alone?

Sorry about the flaming; I'm just getting burnt out by having to
re-explain this numerous times, very often to the same people.

The name "SAIL" is a nickname, as is "SU-AI".  The official name of
that system is "SU-AI.ARPA".  Only that name should ever be used in
SMTP and in message headers (both RFC 821 and 822 state this).

Nicknames should only be used in the user interface.  They should
be immediately translated to the official name.  I realize that a
lot of software fails to do this.  That is the only reason why no
software enforces this.  I would be deludged with complaints from
users if the TOPS-20 SMTP server or message reply mechanism rejected
non-official names.

However, our generosity in accepting a set of nicknames shouldn't
be stretched to meaning we should accept all possible ways in which
nicknames can be used, including the artificial application of ".ARPA"
to those names.

It is NOT correct to apply ".ARPA" to Internet names.  It is NOT
correct to use ".ARPA" as a flag indicating Internet delivery.  Sometime
soon there will be other top-level domains in use on the Internet besides
".ARPA".  All that software which has ".ARPA" wired in will break.

Mark Crispin
Panda Programming
